#### 155. Reeds in the Wind
##### Grazia Deledda
##### fatalistic · honor · redemption

This haunting, lyrical novel uses a vivid regionalist narrative style to portray the lives of three impoverished noble sisters in a remote Sardinian village. It explores the struggle to maintain personal dignity and family honor against a backdrop of inexorable economic decline, set within a landscape of windswept hills, ruins, and local spirits.

Anchored by an aging, deeply loyal family servant whose secret past guilt drives his dedication to his mistresses, the story is deeply superstitious. Rigid social hierarchies, unwritten blood codes, and a pervasive belief in fate leave little room for individual freedom on the exhausting journey toward moral penance.

##### Fiction, 1913, 220 pages

