#### 156. Pygmalion
##### George Bernard Shaw
##### witty · class · independence

This sharp, hilarious social comedy features a swift, intellectual dialogue style that skewers class pretension and societal hypocrisy. The transformation of a working-class flower girl into a refined lady becomes a fierce critique of the elite drawing rooms of Edwardian London.

A brilliant but arrogant phonetics professor bets he can pass off a flower girl as a duchess simply by changing her speech. Subverting traditional romance tropes, the heroine develops a fierce self-worth and class consciousness, demanding respect on her own terms and refusing to be a passive experiment.

##### Fiction, 1913, 150 pages

