#### 159. The Village
##### Ivan Bunin
##### bleak · rural · decay

This uncompromising, naturalistic novel features a stark, visceral prose style that strips away the romantic mythology of rural Russian life to reveal systemic poverty and ignorance. It is an intense, bleak look at the collapse of rural life before the Russian Revolution, following two brothers—a cynical merchant and a peasant poet.

Rejecting traditional romantic subplots, the story offers an episodic look at rural decay, domestic violence, and economic stagnation. Attempts to reform properties or educate neighbors are systematically crushed by the profound, historical weight of rural inertia and lack of education.

