This profound philosophical treatise features an earnest, deeply analytical prose style that directly addresses the existential confusion and search for higher purpose. It calls for a rejection of shallow materialism in favor of an active spiritual life, asserting that human beings are active creators of moral value.

Systematically criticizing contemporary scientific and social philosophies, the text builds toward the author’s own framework of "activism." Structural dichotomies between the merely natural world and the higher spiritual reality guide the reader through complex ethical problems to foster an independent, purposeful worldview.

